.chap(|Errors, Suspension, and Text Editing|,editing)

This chapter describes some of the important interactive features
of PPL.  As we have already seen, the user types commands
to PPL at the !<top level>, possibly invoking one or more
functions consisting of any number of stored statements.
PPL also allows the user to control
execution at the level of these stored statements, to examine
or change the values of local variables after an error, and
to make changes in the text of functions.  We shall now take
up each of these topics in turn.

.sec(Syntax Errors,synerr)
.x syntax error
.x error,syntax

A !<syntax error> is detected by PPL
immediately after the user has typed in
a statement.
The error may be some sort of illegal format
in an editing command, or it may be
an error such as unbalanced parentheses
in a statement.  In all cases, PPL prints
out a message that attempts to pinpoint the
source of the error.
Whenever a syntax error is detected
by PPL, none of the given statement will have been executed.
If a line of a function was being typed,
PPL will repeat the line number and
await a corrected version.

Note that after an error, as well as at any other
time, the  most recently typed statement may be reopened
for editing simply by pressing the <<Escape> key.
The mechanisms for text editing are
presented in Sections {section! textedit} and {section! charedit}.

.sec(Execution Errors,exerr)

The second class of errors occurs during
actual !<execution> of a statement.
Such errors as attempts to use an %<unassigned/variable>
in an expression can be detected
by PPL only when the statement containing the
expression is actually executed.
Messages indicating %<execution/error>s are
preceded either by the words "Execution error"
or by an indication of what built-in function
was being executed when the error was detected.
The next line typed indicates where execution
was stopped.  The message "Stopped in direct statement"
means that the error was detected within a line
the user had typed in for immediate execution.
(The message is omitted if this is clear from context.)
However, if the message is "Stopped in line"
followed by a function name and line number,
the error was detected during the execution of a user function.
In this case, we say that execution has been
!<suspended> within the @/<function,suspension/of> in question.
PPL indicates its readiness to accept a command
from the user in the suspended state by typing
the characters 3S>1 in the eight spaces where it usually indents.

While in this suspended state, the user
may issue statements to be immediately executed,
just as he could while in the !<global>
.see top level,global
(top level) @<environment,global> in which PPL was started.
However, such statements are now interpreted
in the @<environment,suspended> of the suspended function;
that is, the %<procedure/identifier>, the formals,
.x dummy argument
.x argument,dummy
the &<local/variable>s, and the <<label>s are accessible as
if the immediate statement were a line of the
function itself.

The user is even allowed to change the values
of any variables whose names are accessible
in the current environment, and to resume
execution at any statement in the function
by means of a ~<<GOTO>~ to that statement.
Typing ~<<RESUME>~ (i.e. calling the built-in parameterless
function called ~RESUME~) will cause the
statement that produced the error to be started
over.  Thus, if the error was due to an %<unassigned/variable>,
for example, we could continue execution by assigning
the appropriate value and typing ~RESUME~.

If the error is such that we cannot usefully
resume execution, we may escape to the @<global environment,escaping to>
by calling the built-in function
~<<RESET>~.  A successful ~RESET~
is signified by the fact that PPL again indents
for a user command, but without typing 3S>1.
Certain other operations, such as editing the text
of a suspended function, will also cause an
.x RESET,automatic
.x automatic RESET
automatic ~RESET~
to be performed and a warning message typed.

.sec(User Suspension,suspension)
.x manual suspension
.x suspension,manual

Occasionally it is necessary for
execution of a program to be prematurely
terminated (because it has gone into an
%<infinite/loop>, for example).
To do so, the user should type <<Control-C> (twice in PPL-10).
PPL will suspend execution and print out
the name of the current function and the number
of the statement it was executing.*<If the result of your typing Control-C is that
the system prints '.' or '@' at the left margin, then
control has fallen out of PPL and into the timesharing monitor.
You should immediately issue a ~REENTER~ command to
return control to PPL.>
.x REENTER

The user may now type statements for immediate
execution in the %/<environment/of/suspension>,
exactly as in the case where an error has occurred.
Execution may be resumed if desired by typing 3<<RESUME>1,
or may be begun at another statement by the use of
the ~<<GOTO>~ operation.
Using ~RESUME~ in this case will cause PPL to continue
!<exactly> where it left off when it was interrupted by the user.
This is in contrast with the use of ~RESUME~ after an error,
when the statement in error is started over.

The following protocol illustrates some
possible errors and an example of user suspension.
We are attempting to write a function {fn(PRIME,n)}
which takes an argument of type ~INT~ and returns either
~TRUE~ or ~FALSE~ depending on whether or not the number is prime
(i.e. evenly divisible only by itself and one).

.examp
.tabs 9,31
\$PRIME(N); I
   [1]\I_2
   [2]\IF I^2 > N THEN RETURN TRUE
   [3]\IF I*IDIV(N,I) = N THEN RETURN FALSE
   [4]\GOTO %2
   [5]\$

.apart group
\PRIME(2)
TRUE\\7Apparently correct results.3
\PRIME(3)
TRUE
\PRIME(4(\7User makes a typing error.3
\       ^---SYNTAX ERROR
\PRIME(4)\7Retyped input correctly.3
FALSE
.apart group
\PRIME(5)
^C\\7Program goes into a loop.3
^C\\7Control-C used to suspend it.3
STOPPED BEFORE EXECUTING PRIME[4]
     S> N\7Examining local variables in3
5\\7  environment of suspension.3
     S> I
2
     S> RESUME\7Resuming execution.3
^C\\7Function resumes but is still in loop.3
^C\\7  User must suspend it again.3
STOPPED BEFORE EXECUTING PRIME[3]
     S> I\7Value hasn't changed - there3
2\\7  is a bug in the program.3
.apart group
     S> $PRIME[3.5]\7Edit the function, using text3
[RESET EXECUTED]\7  editing facilities explained3
 [3.5]\I_I+1\7  in {"Section!" textedit}.3
 [3.6]\$

\PRIME(5)\7Operation now correct.3
TRUE
\PRIME(13)
TRUE
\PRIME(14)
FALSE
.end

.sec(Demanding Input from the User,demand)

There is a third case which we might
consider a suspension, though it really is not.
A running program will request input from the
user when it encounters a @@<question mark,denoting demand symbol>
(called the !<demand symbol>) in a statement.
The expression now typed in by the user
will be evaluated and substituted for the
<<demand symbol>, and execution will continue.

This feature is useful for talkative
programs that require input during their execution.
A statement containing a demand symbol should
usually be preceded by a statement that prints
a message explaining what is being requested from the user.
The following is a trivial example
of the use of the demand symbol:

.examp
.tabs 9,31
\$<<SQUARE>
   [1]\"HI. I FIND SQUARES."
   [2]\"GIVE ME A NUMBER, PLEASE."
   [3]\N_?
   [4]\"THE SQUARE OF THAT NUMBER IS"
   [5]\N^2
   [6]\$

.apart group
\SQUARE
HI. I FIND SQUARES.
GIVE ME A NUMBER, PLEASE.
      ? 29\7Question mark typed by PPL.3
THE SQUARE OF THAT NUMBER IS
841
.end

A question mark followed by a @@<double quote,in STRING demand symbol>
(3?"1) is the !<STRING demand symbol>, and is
.x STRING demand symbol
.x demand symbol,STRING
similar to the normal demand symbol except that
the user's reply is returned as a ~STRING~
rather than being evaluated.
For example:

.examp
\S_?"
      ? MY NAME IS BILL
\S
MY NAME IS BILL
.end

.sec(Text Editing,textedit)
.x text editing
.x editing,text

PPL has an extensive program editing
mechanism that may be used any time
PPL is requesting input from the user,
except in the case of a string demand symbol (3?"1).
Basically, what we can do is open an existing
function for editing, make changes via insertion,
deletion, or updating, and close the function
again.

Opening a function for editing consists
.xx editing,opening function,for
.see function editing,editing
of typing a @@<dollar sign,to open function for editing>, the function name, and
a line number enclosed in @@<square brackets,enclosing line number in editing command>.
PPL responds by typing the line number
at the left margin.  A new statement may
now be typed to replace the old statement
.x replacing statement in function
.x statement,replacing
with that number.

Pressing Return causes the
.x Return key
newly-typed statement to replace the old,
except that if the replacement line is empty
(i.e. just Return is typed)
the old line will not be replaced.
PPL responds by typing
the number of the next statement in sequence.
This statement is in turn open for replacement if
desired.

To edit a statement which is not the next
in sequence, the user should type a command consisting
only of the number of the statement to be edited, enclosed
in square brackets.  This line is
interpreted as an editing command and
does not replace the current statement.  PPL
responds by typing the number of the new statement
at the left margin.

A statement may be inserted between two others
.x inserting statement in function
.x statement,inserting
by specifying a !<Dewey-decimal> line number
.x Dewey-decimal
containing a decimal point and a one or two digit
fractional part.  Thus, to insert a new statement between
statements [2] and [3], one might input a statement [2.5].
When Return is typed after this line, PPL sequences
to statement [2.6] automatically.  Note that this sequencing
is Dewey-decimal, so that [2.9] sequences to [2.10].

The function is closed by typing a line
containing only a @/<dollar sign,closing function/with>.  This again is interpreted
only as an editing command, and the dollar sign
does not replace the current statement.

These operations become clearer by the use of
an example.  We wish to define a function
that will compute the sum of all the prime
numbers between two limits specified as arguments.
This is to be done using the ~<<PRIME>~ function
defined in {"Section!" suspension}.  The function entered
below is incorrect and causes an execution error.

.examp
\$<<SUMPRIME>(I,J)
   [1]\FOR C_I:J DOTHRU %2
   [2]\IF PRIME(C) THEN SUMPRIME_SUMPRIME+C
   [3]\$

\SUMPRIME(5,10)
IN SYSTEM FN ADD:  IMPROPER ARGUMENT TYPE
STOPPED IN SUMPRIME[2]
     S> SUMPRIME
LOCAL SUMPRIME HAS NO VALUE IN CURRENT ENVIRONMENT
     S>
.end

The main problem is that we have forgotten to assign
an initial value of zero to the procedure identifier
~SUMPRIME~;  thus, in statement [2] the ~ADD~
function (invoked by the '+' operator) fails
because one of its operands has no value.
This causes an execution error and suspension.
We then ask for the value of ~SUMPRIME~ (in the environment
of suspension) and verify that it is indeed undefined.

We now want to insert a statement before line [1]
of ~SUMPRIME~ to initialize the @/<procedure identifier,initialization/of>
to zero.  While we are at it, we shall
also change the function header so as to declare ~C~
local.  Though the function will work perfectly well
with ~C~ being global, it is good programming practice
always to declare &<local/variable> all variables that need
not be accessible outside the local environment.
This is particularly true of common variable names
(e.g. single letters) that might also be used in other
functions.
The required editing is as follows:

.examp
     S> $SUMPRIME[0.5]
[RESET EXECUTED]
 [0.5]\SUMPRIME_0
 [0.6]\[0]
   [0]\$SUMPRIME(I,J); C
   [1]\$

\SUMPRIME(5,10)
12
\SUMPRIME(1,100)
1061
.end

We first request PPL to open the function ~SUMPRIME~
at line [0.5], meaning that we want to insert a statement
between lines [0] (the function header) and [1].
Note that editing a suspended function causes PPL
to execute a ~@<RESET,automatic>~ automatically.
After inserting line [0.5], we press Return, and
PPL now expects the user to type in a line [0.6];
however, we wish to change the @<function header,editing>
(considered to be line [0] during text editing),
so we type zero in square brackets and press Return.
After typing in a corrected line [0], we press
Return and PPL sequences to statement [1],
which we could now change if we wanted to.
However, we type a dollar sign to close the function
with no further changes.
A few calls to ~SUMPRIME~ now seem to indicate
correct operation.

To find out exactly what our editing has done to
the ~SUMPRIME~ function, we now !<display> it.
.x displaying function
.x function,displaying
This is done by typing a @@<question mark,to display function> followed
by the name of the function:

.examp
\? SUMPRIME
.SKIP 1
\$SUMPRIME(I,J); C
   [1]\SUMPRIME_0
   [2]\FOR C_I:J DOTHRU %3
   [3]\IF PRIME(C) THEN SUMPRIME_SUMPRIME+C
\$
.end

The first thing that may be noticed is that
the statements have been renumbered
.xx function,automatic renumbering,of
using sequential line numbers.
This operation is performed automatically upon
closing the function.
The second item of note is that, in statement [2]
(previously statement [1]), the statement reference
3%21 has been changed to 3%31, thus continuing
to refer to the statement it previously referred to.
Whenever PPL renumbers lines, it performs this
conversion on all !<relocatable line numbers>.
A %<relocatable/line number> is a decimal number of
one to three digits preceded by a @@<percent sign,introducing relocatable line number>.
During execution, a @/<relocatable line number,value/of>
is exactly the same as an ~INT~; its special properties
come into play only during text editing.

(PPL cannot, at present, correctly process
a reference to a statement whose line number
contains a Dewey-decimal fractional part.
To generate a correct reference, the function
must first be closed and re-opened; doing so
will cause the statement in question to be given
an integer statement number, and all will be well.
This restriction may be removed in some future version of PPL).

A few other remarks should be made at this point.
First, all editing operations presented thus far are also
available while typing in a function for the first time;
e.g. when PPL requests statement [6], we may go back
and re-open statement [3] for editing,
or insert a new statement such as [3.5].

Second, a new or replacement statement not in sequence
may be inserted by specifying a statement number
in square brackets followed, on the same line, by the
(non-blank) new text of the statement; i.e. it is not
necessary to type a Return after the statement
number and wait for PPL to respond with that
statement number at the left margin.

Finally, if in the process of editing a function we decide
that we have made such a mess of it that we want to
escape and try again, we may do so by typing
@/<Control-C,aborting editing/with> (followed by 3<<REENTER>1 if necessary).
This will nullify
the effect of all editing since the function was
last opened.

.sec(Displaying the Text of Functions,displaying)

In the preceding section we displayed
the text of the function ~SUMPRIME~
by typing the special command 3?SUMPRIME1.
The text of any user-defined function may
similarly be displayed in the same manner.
To display a single statement rather than an entire
@/<function,displaying single statement/of>, the user may specify a statement
number in @@<square brackets,in display command>; for example:

.examp
\?PRIME[3]
   [3]\IF I*IDIV(N,I) = N THEN RETURN FALSE
.end

A group of statements in a function may similarly be displayed
by specifying the first and last statement numbers, separated
by a colon.  For example:

.examp
\?EUCLID[0:1]
\$EUCLID(M,N); R
   [1]\R _ M-N*IDIV(M,N)
.end

.sec(Advanced Text Editing,charedit)
.x text editing,advanced

The line-by-line program editing facilities presented so far
are sufficient for performing a majority of all modifications
that need to be made to PPL programs.  However, there are some
situations in which more powerful facilities are needed, such as
when it is desired to systematically change all occurrences of
some variable name to some other name.  PPL therefore provides
a fairly complete, general-purpose text editing subsystem
that may be called into use when necessary.*<At the time this edition
of the manual was prepared, PPL-10 did not yet contain this
advanced editing capability.  A character-by-character editing
facility to be found in versions prior to 53 is documented
in {"Appendix" apsup10}.>

The text editor may be entered at any time when PPL is awaiting
user typein by pressing the <<Escape> key (sometimes labelled
.see Alt-Mode,Escape
Alt-Mode or Esc).  If this is done before or during typein of
a direct statement, then the statement being typed in (if any)
or the entire text of the previous direct statement (if not)
becomes the text to be edited.  If, however, a function is
open for editing, the statement being typed in (if any)
is entered as the current statement, and this statement
becomes the default text to be edited.

PPL then prints an asterisk ('*') at the left margin
to signal that the text editor has been entered.
The remainder of this section is devoted to describing
the commands that may be issued to the text editor.
Text editor mode may be left by simply pressing Return
in response to the editor's '*', at which point PPL
re-translates all affected statements and executes or stores
them as appropriate and returns to normal command input mode.

.ssec(Text Editor Command Format,textcom)

Commands to the text editor consist of complete lines,
terminated by Return.  The usual control characters may
be used to correct mistakes (<<Rubout> and <<Control-U> in
the DECsystem-10 and Unix versions of PPL, and <<Control-A>
and <<Control-Q> in the Tenex version), and commands may be
continued on subsequent lines by use of the percent sign convention
described earlier.

The general form of a text editing command is as follows:

.begin nofill indent 8

[ !<range> ] !<repetition> !<verb> !<string>{sub(1)} $ !<string>{sub(2)}
.end

Not all fields are required for every command and default values
will be supplied by PPL as explained below.
'$' stands for the Escape (or Alt-Mode) character,
which echoes as a dollar sign, and is required to terminate
the !<string>{sub(1)} if a !<string>{sub(2)} is given.
An Escape is also required following !<string>{sub(2)} if it ends in
the percent-sign character to prevent it from being interpreted
as a continuation line.

The [!<range>] portion of the command determines the
.xx text editing command,range,portion of
range of statement numbers over which the command is to
apply.  This may be a single statement number or a pair of
numbers separated by a colon.  A @@<period,denoting current statement> ('.') may be used
to denote the current statement, or an @@<asterisk,denoting entire function> ('*') to
denote the entire function.  Hence, 3[3]1, 3[2:7]1,
3[1,.]1, 3[.,13]1, and 3[*]1 are all legal
range specifications.  If the range specification is omitted,
the command applies only to the current statement.
The range specification is illegal unless a function is
being edited.

The !<repetition> is a positive integer determining the number
.xx text editing command,repetition,portion of
of times the command is to be repeated.  It is relevant only
in those commands that search for and operate on strings.
A repetition count of '*' (an @@<asterisk,denoting indefinite repetition>) indicates that the
command is to be repeated indefinitely, i.e. as many times as
is possible in the specified range.  The default repetition count
is one.

The !<verb> specifies the operation to be performed.  It is made up
.xx editing command,verb,portion of
of alphanumeric characters, and may be abbreviated to any
unique initial substring (note that at present all commands are
uniquely determined by their first character).  The verb must
be followed by a non-alphanumeric character if any string
arguments follow it.  If the delimiter is a space,
it is not included as the first character of !<string>{sub(1)};  but if
it is anything but a space, it is included.  Characters after the
delimiter are included in !<string>{sub(1)}
even if they are spaces.  (In the @@<Tenex,editing command recognition in> version, command recognition
will be carried out if @/<Escape,editing command recognition/with> is struck during typein of the verb.
Recognition consists of typing out the remainder of the command
and the terminating space.)

!<string>{sub(1)} and !<string>{sub(2)} are sequences of one or more legal
.xx editing command,string argument,in
PPL characters.
Various commands take zero, one, or two string arguments.
Excess strings are ignored (a warning message is typed out).

.ssec(Current Statement and Character Position,textcur)

The !<current statement> is a particular statement in the
.x current statement
.x current character position
currently open function (if there is one), and the !<current
character position> is a pointer lying between two adjacent
characters in the current statement, or at the
beginning of the statement.  All <<string search>es in commands
with no range specification or with a specification of the
form 3[.:!<n>]1 (where !<n> is a statement number) begin at the
current character position.

The character position is reset to the beginning of the
current statement at the !<end> of the commands ~INSERT~, ~REPLACE~, and ~DELETE~ as well
as ~FIND~ commands which are unsuccessful.
The current statement number is not changed by any command except ~FIND~.
Commands other than ~FIND~ that perform string searches through
specified ranges of statements temporarily leave the character
pointer at the end of the last string searched for so as to
be able to perform repetitions, but never change the current statement number
and always reset the character position to the beginning of the
current statement when they are finished.

.ssec(Individual Commands,textdesc)

.macro desc 
.if lines<6 then next page
.skip 1
.begin nofill indent 8 select 3
. 

The following are the individual text editor commands and
their functions:

.desc
[!<r>] !<n> @/<REPLACE,editing command/> !<string>{sub(1)} $ !<string>{sub(2)}
.end

In the range !<r>, replace the first !<n> occurrences of !<string>{sub(1)} by
!<string>{sub(2)}.

.desc
[!<r>] !<n> @/<DELETE,editing command/> !<string>{sub(1)}
.end

In the range !<r>, delete the first !<n> occurrences of !<string>{sub(1)}.

.desc
[!<r>] !<n> @/<INSERT,editing command/> !<string>{sub(1)} $ !<string>{sub(2)}
.end

In the range !<r>, insert !<string>{sub(1)} after the first !<n> occurrences
of !<string>{sub(2)}.  If !<string>{sub(2)} is not supplied, insert !<string>{sub(1)} !<n> times at
the current pointer position.

.desc
[!<r>] !<n> @/<FIND,editing command/> !<string>{sub(1)}
.end

In the range !<r>, find the !<n>th occurrence of !<string>{sub(1)}, and
leave the current character pointer at the end of that string.
This command also changes the current statement to be the
one in which the !<n>th occurrence of !<string>{sub(1)} was found.
If !<string>{sub(1)} is empty, ~FIND~ uses the string argument to
the most recent ~FIND~ as its default.
If there are less than !<n> occurrences of !<string>{sub(1)} in the
given range, the character pointer is reset to the beginning
of the line that was current when the ~FIND~ command was issued.

.desc
[!<r>] @/<TYPE,editing command/>
.end

Type out all the statements in the range !<r>.
Repetition and string specifications are illegal.

.desc
[!<r>] @/<KILL,editing command/>
.end

Delete all statements in the range !<r>.  Repetition and string specifications
are illegal.

.desc
@/<VERBOSE,editing command/>
.end

Enter verbose mode, in which an automatic ~TYPE~ command is
executed after every command that uses string arguments.
Range, repetition, and string arguments are illegal.

.desc
@/<CONCISE,editing command/>
.end

Leave verbose mode.  Range, repetition, and string arguments
are illegal.

For compatibility with normal PPL line editor commands,
the following commands may also be given to the text editor:

.desc
[!<n>]
.end

(i.e. a command consisting entirely of a single statement number
in square brackets)  Make statement !<n> be the current statement,
and reset the current character position to the beginning of
that statement.

.desc
$
.end

(i.e. just a dollar sign)  Exit the text editor and close
the current function, just as occurs when '$' is typed as
a command to the line editor.
